# INSTITUTIONAL STRUCTURE OF TRUST-BASED ORGANISATIONS v0.1
(Trust Application Layer — Cooperative Boundary)

Author: Kok Pian Gew  
Date: 2026  
Status: Conceptual Draft (v0.1)

---

## 1. PURPOSE

This document defines how cooperative systems can be structured
as institutions under the Trust Framework and Continuation Framework.

It describes:

- how contribution is coordinated
- how value is created and distributed
- how authority emerges
- how institutional stability is maintained

This is not a moral prescription.

It is a structural framework describing how institutions can operate
under continuation constraints.

---

## 2. POSITION IN FRAMEWORK STACK

This framework sits within:

Continuation → Coexistence Systems → Cooperative Boundary → Institutional Form

It operationalises:

- Trust (interpretation mechanism)
- Credibility (stabilised signal)
- Credit (forward coordination)

into:

> **Institutional coordination structures**

---

## 3. INSTITUTIONAL PRIMITIVE

> **An organisation is a contribution-based coordination system that converts participation capacity into value under continuation constraints.**

---

## 4. CORE MECHANISM

All institutional activity follows:

Contribution  
→ Signal  
→ Attribution  
→ Value Realisation  
→ Reward Distribution  
→ Credibility Formation

---

## 5. DUAL-CAPACITY STRUCTURE (TOKEN INTERPRETATION)

Institutional coordination separates:

### 5.1 Participation Capacity (Base Layer)

Represents:

- time
- effort
- skill allocation

Properties:

- must be allocated to generate value
- unused capacity produces no signal
- persistent non-participation reduces coordination authority

---

### 5.2 Value Realisation (Outcome Layer)

Represents:

- realised economic value
- project outcomes

Properties:

- derived from completed work
- distributed based on verified contribution
- tied to real economic output

---

## 6. CONTRIBUTION LEDGER

All verified contributions are recorded as signals.

Ledger structure:

- contributor
- project
- activity
- timestamp
- verified outcome

The ledger forms the basis for:

- attribution
- credibility
- coordination authority

---

## 7. VALUE DISTRIBUTION STRUCTURE

Economic output is divided into:

### 7.1 Labour Margin
- distributed to contributors
- proportional to verified contribution

### 7.2 Coordination Margin
- compensates organisation and management
- derived from enabling cooperation, not extraction

### 7.3 Institutional Reserve
- ensures continuation capacity
- absorbs volatility and supports long-term stability

---

## 8. AUTHORITY MODEL

Authority emerges from:

- verified contribution
- accumulated credibility
- demonstrated coordination capability

Ownership and authority are separated.

---

## 9. FOUNDER AND HISTORICAL CONTRIBUTION

Initial contributions are recognised but decay over time
unless renewed.

Multi-horizon recognition preserves:

- short-term contribution (reward)
- medium-term contribution (credibility)
- long-term contribution (legitimacy)

---

## 10. CIRCULATION AND STABILITY

Institutional stability depends on:

> **circulation of participation capacity through productive activity**

Two failure modes:

### Under-circulation
- idle capacity
- declining contribution signals
- reduced cooperation

### Over-circulation
- excessive project creation
- weak verification
- signal inflation

---

## 11. STABILITY CONDITIONS

An institution remains stable when:

- contribution is verifiable
- value reflects real outcomes
- coordination capacity matches activity level
- signals remain meaningful
- circulation remains balanced

---

## 12. GOVERNANCE STRUCTURE

Institutional change is:

- bounded
- gradual
- subject to continuation constraint

Governance operates through:

- structured decision domains
- limited movement per cycle
- feasibility validation

---

## 13. CONTINUATION CONSTRAINT

Institutions must remain:

- economically viable
- operationally stable
- signal-coherent
- governance-capable

If continuation fails:

- system degrades
- core functions are preserved
- exit occurs without violating institutional principles

---

## 14. COOPERATIVE BOUNDARY

This framework defines the boundary at which:

> **cooperation remains stable and productive**

Beyond this boundary:

- signals lose meaning
- coordination fails
- extraction dominates

---

## 15. RELATIONSHIP TO EXISTING FORMS

This framework generalises beyond:

- mutual organisations
- cooperatives
- partnership models

It introduces:

- contribution-based authority (not ownership-based)
- dynamic influence (not static rights)
- signal-based coordination (not role-based hierarchy)

---

## 16. INTERPRETATION

This is not a normative model of fairness.

It is:

> **a structural model of how institutions must operate to sustain cooperation under uncertainty**

---

## 17. CORE FORMULATION

> **Institutions are systems that convert participation capacity into value through verified contribution, and remain stable only when circulation, attribution, and coordination operate within continuation constraints.**

---

